                    h3 Is Trash The New Avocado Toast?
                    p
                        | Teflon has a trash problem -- and the only cure is more trash, according to a handful of millennials who abandoned their upscale apartments in gentrifying neighborhoods of New York City and Washington, D.C. for the flaming heaps of garbage accumulating atop the league standings.
                    p
                        | "Poop, LaCroix cans, pickle jars filled with weeks-old linguini," said Kia Rahimian, a 28-year-old trashman who leads the league in scoring by a wide margin, but suffered his first loss of the season to a rival trashman from Brooklyn. "One man's trash is another man's champion."
                    p
                        | League observers in San Francisco praise the intention of their East Coast cohorts, but doubt the results can last much longer. "As our world is crushed under the weight of its own carbon footprint, we support any effort that moves the needle on sustainability," said a spokesman for the Ivy Saliva Clan, an energy startup trying to fuel championships with tried-and-true star power. "But study after study has shown that the undeniable output of players like Devonta Freeman, Kirk Cousins and Brandon Cooks is the only way to win in the long run."
